<cards>
   <title>NBA All-Stars</title>

   <card>
      <question>
         Center, UCLA. During his career with the NBA's Milwaukee Bucks and Los
         Angeles Lakers from 1969 to 1989, he scored more points than any other
         player in league history and won a record six MVP Awards and six NBA
         championships.
      </question>
      <answer>Kareem Abdul-Jabbar</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Center, LSU. 7' 1", 325 pounds. Drafted by the Orlando Magic
         with the first overall pick of the 1992 NBA draft.  Rookie of the year
         in 1992-93.  Later played for the LA Lakers, Miami Head, Phoenix Suns,
         and Cleveland Cavaliers.
      </question>
      <answer>Shaquille O'Neal</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Shooting guard, UNC Chapel Hill.  Abruptly retired from
         basketball at the beginning of the 1993-94 NBA season to pursue a
         career in baseball. Rejoined the Chicago Bulls in 1995 and led them to
         three additional championships
      </question>
      <answer>Michael Jordan</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Power forward, Louisiana Tech. Played 18 seasons as the star player of
         the Utah Jazz.
      </question>
      <answer>Karl Malone</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Guard, West Virginia. Nicknames "Mr. Clutch" and "The Logo".  Played
         entire career with the LA Lakers.  Later Head Coach and General
         Manager of the Lakers.
      </question>
      <answer>Jerry West</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Center, Kansas. 7' 1", 300 lb.  Started pro career with the Harlem
         Globetrotters, later played with Philadelpha Warriors, 76ers, and LA
         Lakers.  First player to score 100 points in an NBA game.
      </question>
      <answer>Wilt Chamberlain</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Point guard, Holy Cross. Boston Celtics (1950-1963).
      </question>
      <answer>Bob Cousy</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Power forward, first player since 1975 to be drafted directly out of
         high school.  Minnesota Timberwolves (1995-2007), Boston Celtics
         (2007-present).
      </question>
      <answer>Kevin Garnett</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Forward/Guard, Ohio State.  Drafted by Boston Celtics 1962, played his
         entire 16-year career there.  Immortalized for his clutch steal in the
         closing seconds of the 1965 Eastern Conference championship against the
         Philadelphia 76ers
      </question>
      <answer>John Havlicek</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Small forward, power forward, Indiana State. Rival of Magic Johnson.
         Played entire career with the Boston Celtics (1979-1992).  Head coach
         of the Indiana Pacers from 1997 to 2000.
      </question>
      <answer>Larry Bird</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Shooting guard.  LA Lakers (1996-present).  All-time leading scorer in
         Lakers history. Spent childhood years in Italy where his father played
         professional basketball.
      </question>
      <answer>Kobe Bryant</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Power forward, Wake Forest.  From U. S. Virgin Islands. Pro career San
         Antonio Spurs (1997-present)
      </question>
      <answer>Tim Duncan</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Guard, Georgetown. 1996 1st round draft pick. Philadelphia 76ers (1996-present)
      </question>
      <answer>Allen Iverson</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Center, San Francisco.  Boston Celtics (1956-1969).  Longtime rival of
         Wilt Chamberlain.
      </question>
      <answer>Bill Russell</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Power forward, Auburn. Philadelphia 76ers (1984-1992), then 4 years
         each with the Phoenix Suns and the Houston Rockets.  Throughout his
         career, argued that professional athletes should not be considered
         role models. Has considered running for Governor of Alabama.
      </question>
      <answer>Charles Barkley</answer>
   </card>

   <card>
      <question>
         Center, Georgetown.  From Kingston, Jamaica. 15 year career with the
         NY Knicks.  Now head coach of the Orlando Magic.
      </question>
      <answer>Patrick Ewing</answer>
   </card>

</cards>
